{{for|Arca's 2017 album|Arca (album)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Arca | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | image = Arca DJ Set at Home Sweet Home (cropped).jpg | image_size = 210px | alt = | caption = Arca DJing in New York City | birth_name = Alejandro Ghersi | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|10|14|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]] | origin = | genre = {{hlist|[[Electronic music|Electronic]]|[[Experimental music|experimental]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Eede |first=Christian |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/16230-arca-announces-new-album-xen |title=Listen: Arca – Thievery |work=[[The Quietus]] |date=11 September 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>|[[Intelligent dance music|IDM]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Houlihan |first=Finn |title=Listen: Arca – 'Thievery' |url=http://www.acclaimmag.com/music/listen-arca-thievery |website=Acclaim Magazine |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>|[[industrial hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeout.com/tokyo/clubs/arca |title=Arca |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>|[[avant-pop]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Morse |first=Eric |title=Arca Talks Working With Bjork, Screaming About Sex, Explosive New LP |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/arca-talks-working-with-bjork-screaming-about-sex-explosive-new-lp-20151117 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref>}} | occupation = {{hlist|Record producer|DJ|songwriter|singer|{{nowrap|mixing engineer}}}} | years_active = 2011–present | label = {{hlist|[[XL Recordings|XL]]|[[Mute Records|Mute]]|[[Hippos in Tanks]]|UNO NYC|Poni Republic|Nang|Soundsister}} | associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Björk]]|[[FKA twigs]]|[[Kelela]]|[[Kanye West]]|[[Jesse Kanda]]}} | website = {{URL|arca1000000.com}} }}
'''Alejandro Ghersi''' (born 14 October 1989), better known by his stage name '''Arca''', is a Venezuelan electronic record producer, songwriter, mixing engineer and DJ based in [[Dalston]], [[London]].<ref name="Fader">{{cite web |last=Friedlander |first=Emile |url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/09/30/arca-producer-xen-interview-cover-story |title=Arca Finds Xen |work=[[The Fader]] |date=30 September 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Saville |first=Chad |url=http://beautifulsavage.com/music/feature-venezuelan-producer-arca-going-huge |title=Venezuelan producer Arca is going to be huge. |work=Beautiful Savage |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Saxelby |first=Ruth |url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/07/29/arca-dj-tour-total-freedom-jesse-kanda |title=Arca Announces DJ Tour with Total Freedom and Jesse Kanda |work=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> He has released three studio albums to critical praise and has produced for artists such as [[Björk]], [[Kanye West]], [[FKA twigs]], [[Kelela]] and [[Frank Ocean]].
==Early life== Arca was born in [[Caracas, Venezuela]]. His father was an investment banker and his mother studied International Studies. His family moved to Connecticut for a time, before returning to Venezuela, where he was privately educated and was introduced to piano lessons. He describes his childhood as "kind of in a bubble", and had difficulty accepting the fact that he was [[gay]]. He released music in his teen years by the name of Nuuro, and received moderate popularity in his home country, with praise from big national artists such as [[Los Amigos Invisibles]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/oct/31/arca-bjork-kanye-west |title=Arca: 'Nothing is off limits emotionally' |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> He later attended the [[Clive Davis Institute of Recorded Music]] at [[NYU]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Zeichner |first=Naomi |url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/10/29/gen-f-arca |title=GEN F: Arca |work=[[The Fader]] |date=29 October 2012 |accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>
==Career== On 1 February 2012, Arca released his debut [[extended play]] (EP), ''Baron Libre'', through UNO NYC.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hockley-Smith |first=Sam |url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/02/01/download-arcas-debut-ep-baron-libre |title=Download Arca's Debut EP Baron Libre |work=[[The Fader]] |date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Later that year, he released the ''Stretch 1'' and ''Stretch 2'' EPs on 19 April and 6 August respectively.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hockley-Smith |first=Sam |url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/04/19/download-arcas-stretch-1-ep |title=Download Arca's Stretch 1 EP |work=[[The Fader]] |date=19 April 2012 |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ryce |first=Andrew |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/reviews/11498 |title=RA Reviews: Arca - Stretch 2 on UNO (Album) |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=17 August 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>
In 2013, Arca was credited for additional production, programming and songwriting for five of the songs on [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[Yeezus]]'', which was released on 18 June. He also served as one of the three production consultants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://images.modlife.com.s3.amazonaws.com/custom/kanye/YEEZUS-CREDITS.pdf |title=Yeezus Credits |accessdate=25 July 2013 |format=PDF}}</ref> That same year on 23 July, he released his ''[[&&&&&]]'' mixtape through [[SoundCloud]] and [[Hippos in Tanks]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Minsker |first=Evan |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/51615-download-arcas-new-mix |title=Download Arca's New Mix &&&&& |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=23 July 2013 |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The project included an audio-visual performance alongside [[Jesse Kanda]], who contributed the visuals, at [[MoMA PS1]] in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/52452-pitchforks-forms-and-moma-ps1-present-a-multimedia-event-featuring-arca-and-jesse-kanda |title=Pitchfork's FORMS and MoMA PS1 Present a Multimedia Event Featuring Arca and Jesse Kanda |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=27 September 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> On 17 September, [[FKA Twigs]]' ''[[EP2 (FKA Twigs EP)|EP2]]'' was released, on which Arca produced and co-wrote every song.<ref>{{cite web |last=Neyland |first=Nick |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/18590-twigs-ep2 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=19 September 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=FKA Twigs: EP2 Album Review}}</ref>
His debut studio album, ''[[Xen (album)|Xen]]'', was released on 4 November 2014 via [[Mute Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mute.com/mute/signs-to-mute-debut-album-xen-out-on-34-november-hear-the-first-single-thievery |title=Arca Signs to Mute. Debut album Xen out on 3/4 November. Hear the first single Thievery. |work=[[Mute Records]] |accessdate=22 September 2014}}</ref> Arca made significant contributions to [[Björk]]'s ninth studio album ''[[Vulnicura]]'' which was released on 20 January 2015.<ref name="Fader"/> He was credited as the co-producer of seven of the tracks, and the co-writer of two.<ref>{{cite news |last=Michaels |first=Sean |title=Björk working with Kanye producer Arca on next album |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/oct/01/bjork-kanye-west-producer-arca-new-album |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=1 October 2014 |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brandle |first=Lars |title=Bjork Shares Details on New Album 'Vulnicura' |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/6436695/bjork-shares-details-on-new-album-vulnicura |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=14 January 2015 |accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> Arca collaborated with American singer [[Kelela]] on her ''[[Hallucinogen (EP)|Hallucinogen]]'' EP, which was released in October 2015. He's credited for producing, recording, mixing and co-writing two of the tracks, including the title track, which is an instrumental from Arca's ''&&&&&'' mixtape with Kelela adding improvised vocals.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/20432-hallucinogen-ep |title=Kelela: Hallucinogen EP Album Review |work=Pitchfork |date=7 October 2015 |accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref> His second studio album, ''[[Mutant (album)|Mutant]]'', was released on 20 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Minsker |first1=Evan |last2=Strauss |first2=Matthew |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/61485-arca-details-new-album-mutant-shares-en-video |title=Arca Details New Album Mutant, Shares "EN" Video |work=Pitchfork |date=15 October 2015 |accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> He released the ''[[Entrañas]]'' mixtape on 4 July 2016, following the single "Sin Rumbo".
On 22 February 2017, Arca signed with [[XL Recordings]] and released "Piel", the first single from his eponymous third studio album, ''[[Arca (album)|Arca]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.xlr8r.com/news/2017/02/arca-signs-to-xl-recordings |title=Arca Signs to XL Recordings |work=[[XLR8R]] |date=22 February 2017 |accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref> which was released on 7 April 2017 to widespread acclaim from music critics and was featured on numerous year-end lists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/arca/arca/critic-reviews |title=Arca by Arca |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=12 January 2018}}</ref> Later in 2017, Arca collaborated with Björk again on her ninth studio album ''[[Utopia (Björk album)|Utopia]]'', who co-produced the vast majority of the record.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bulut |first=Selim |url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/37206/1/bjork-new-album-interview |title=Björk on finding paradise and her ecstatic return |work=[[Dazed]] |date=5 September 2017 |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> Björk explained that the album explored "the Arca-Björk overlap."<ref>{{cite web |last=Bulut |first=Selim |url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/37420/1/what-we-learnt-from-bjorks-live-qa |title=What we learned from Björk's live Q&A |website=[[Dazed]] |date=15 September 2018 |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> A music video featuring Arca for "[[Arisen My Senses]]" was released on 18 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last=Murphy |first=Sarah |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/bj_rk_documents_her_own_birth_in_arisen_my_senses_video |title=Björk Documents Her Own Birth In "Arisen My Senses" Video |website=[[Exclaim!]] |date=18 December 2017 |accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> Arca also collaborated with Kelela on her debut studio album, ''[[Take Me Apart]]'', released in October 2017. Kelela said he "anchored" the album and produced a bulk of it.<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Price |url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/08/kelela-lmk |title=Kelela Returns with New Song "LMK" |work=Pigeons & Planes |date=1 August 2017 |accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> He's credited for producing on four tracks, and co-writing two.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Take Me Apart |type=CD liner notes |others=[[Kelela]] |publisher=[[Warp (record label)|Warp]] |year=2017}}</ref>
