{{Chinese name|[[Ma (surname)|Ma]]}}
{{Chinese|s=马如龙|t=馬如龍|p=Mǎ Rúlóng|w=Ma Julung|xej=ﻣَﺎ ژُﻮْ ﻟْﻮ}}

'''Ma Rulong''' (Ma Julung in Wade Giles) was a [[Hui people|Chinese Muslim]] who originally rebelled against the [[Qing dynasty]] along with [[Du Wenxiu]] in the [[Panthay Rebellion]]. He later defected to the Qing side.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wlg_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA319&dq=ma+julung&hl=en&ei=twU2TO2APIP88Aaf1cjiAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=ma%20julung&f=false|title=A Short History of China: Being an Account for the General Reader of an Ancient Empire and People|author=Demetrius Charles De Kavanagh Boulger|year=1893|publisher=Allen|location=LONDON 13 WATERLOO PLACE SW|page=319|isbn=|accessdate=2010-06-28}}(Original from Harvard University)</ref> After officially surrendering in 1862 his forces effectively occupied the capital of Yunnan.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Da2M_viEclEC&pg=PA124&dq=ma+lin+muslim&hl=en&ei=NX2qTLHbJoH98AahxJGCDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFAQ6AEwCDgK#v=onepage&q=ma%20lin%20muslim&f=false|title=The Chinese sultanate: Islam, ethnicity, and the Panthay Rebellion in southwest China, 1856–1873|author=David G. Atwill|year=2005|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=|page=124|isbn=0-8047-5159-5|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> He then helped the Qing forces crush his fellow Muslim rebels, and defeated them.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2tNNAAAAMAAJ&dq=ma+julung&q=ma+julung#v=onepage&q=ma%20julung%20viceroy%20despot%20talifoo&f=false|title=The flowery kingdom and the land of the mikado: or, China, Japan, and Corea; containing their complete history down to the present time ...|author1=Henry Davenport Northrop |author2=John Russell Young |year=1894|publisher=C. W. Stanton company|location=CHICAGO|page=130|isbn=|accessdate=2011-07-20}}(Original from the University of Michigan)</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BIMwAQAAIAAJ&dq=ma+julung&q=ma+julung#v=snippet&q=ma%20julung%20viceroy%20despot%20talifoo&f=false|title=The flowery kingdom and the land of the Mikado or China, Japan and Corea: containing their complete history down to the present time : manners, customs, and peculiarities of the people ... : together with a graphic account of the war between China and Japan ...|author=Henry Davenport Northrop|editor=Contributor John Russell Young |year=1894|publisher=International Pub.|location=PHILADELPHIA & CHICAGO|page=130|isbn=|accessdate=2011-07-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-xIoAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA130&dq=ma+julung&hl=en&ei=twU2TO2APIP88Aaf1cjiAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=ma%20julung&f=false|title=The flowery kingdom and the land of the Mikado or China, Japan and Corea: containing their complete history down to the present time; manners, customs and peculiarities of the people; superstitions; idol worship; industries; natural scenery, etc., etc., together with a graphic account of the war between china and Japan, its causes, land and naval battles, etc., etc|author=Henry Davenport Northrop|year=1894|publisher=J.H.Moore Co.|location=|page=130|isbn=|accessdate=2010-06-28}}(Original from Harvard University)[https://books.google.com/books?id=2tNNAAAAMAAJ&dq=ma+julung&q=ma+julung#v=snippet&q=ma%20julung&f=false][https://books.google.com/books?id=BIMwAQAAIAAJ&dq=ma+julung&q=ma+julung#v=snippet&q=ma%20julung&f=false]</ref><ref name="Eliakim Littell, Robert S. Littell, Making of America Project 1900 757">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uEoTAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA757&dq=ma+julung+tung+fu&hl=en&ei=mYQ2TIvFA8L38AbD1vmlAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=ma%20julung%20tung%20fu&f=false|title=The living age ..., Volume 226|author1=Eliakim Littell |author2=Robert S. Littell |author3=Making of America Project |year=1900|publisher=The Living Age Co. Inc.|location=BOSTON|page=757|isbn=|accessdate=2010-06-28}}(Original from the University of Michigan)</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TmnfUKQTym8C&pg=PA620&dq=ma+julung+tung+fu&hl=en&ei=mYQ2TIvFA8L38AbD1vmlAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=ma%20julung%20tung%20fu&f=false|title=The Eclectic magazine: foreign literature|author1=John Holmes Agnew |author2=Walter Hilliard Bidwell |year=1900|publisher=Leavitt, Throw and Co.|location=|page=620|isbn=|accessdate=2010-06-28}}(Original from the University of Michigan)</ref> He was known by the name of [[Yuan Shuai|Marshal]] Ma to Europeans and achieved almost total control in Yunnan province.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tw8MAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA443&dq=like+ma+julung+panthay&hl=en&ei=sIU2TIv9HYP58AbD4a3YAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The history of China, Volume 2|author=Demetrius Charles de Kavanagh Boulger|year=1898|publisher=W. Thacker & co.|location=LONDON|page=443|isbn=|accessdate=2010-06-28}}(Original from Harvard University)</ref> He was the most powerful military official in the province after the war.<ref name="Garnaut">{{cite web|url=http://www.ouigour.fr/recherches_et_analyses/Garnautpage_93.pdf |title=From Yunnan to Xinjiang:Governor Yang Zengxin and his Dungan Generals |last=Garnaut |first=Anthony |publisher=Pacific and Asian History, Australian National University |accessdate=2010-07-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309054654/http://www.ouigour.fr/recherches_et_analyses/Garnautpage_93.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-09 |df= }}</ref>

Du Wenxiu was fought against by the defector to the Qing Ma Rulong. The Muslim scholar [[Ma Dexin]], who said that Neo-Confucianism was reconcilable with Islam, approved of Ma Rulong defecting to the Qing and he also assisted other Muslims in defecting.<ref>{{cite book|author=John King Fairbank|title=The Cambridge History of China: Late Chʻing, 1800-1911, pt. 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pEfWaxPhdnIC&pg=PA213#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=1978|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-22029-3|pages=213–}}</ref>

General Ma Yu-kun, who fought against Japanese forces in the [[First Sino-Japanese War]] and against foreigners in the [[Boxer Rebellion]] was believed to be Ma Rulong's son by Europeans.<ref name="Eliakim Littell, Robert S. Littell, Making of America Project 1900 757"/>

